            <h5 style="margin-left: 10px;">Best practices & Optimal usage</h5>
            <div style="margin-left: 15px;">
                <p>Here are some tips and tricks for using this app optimally</p>
                <ul>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Navigation:</strong>
                        <p>Aside from using the scroll to top button and the '<kbd>CTRL</kbd> + <kbd>T</kbd>', you can now click the page top header to scroll to the page top.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Educations:</strong>
                        <p>It is recommended you create multiple educations for one education. This way you have different parts of your education separated for a better overview.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Descriptions:</strong>
                        <p>Descriptions are optional, but they can help you find your entries. It is recommended to always add a description. Descriptions do not have to be long, but they should properly describe your entry.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Institutions:</strong>
                        <p>You can add the name of the institute of your education. It is recommended you add this to your educations to better find your entries. Use the following convention for adding institutions. "SI, Some Institution"</p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Data:</strong>
                        <p>
                            It is recommended that you sometimes back up your data. You can do this by copying the file '<code>GradeMaster.db</code>' and save it somewhere at a dedicated location. The file is located at: '<code>C:\Users\[YourUser]\AppData\Local\GradeMaster\Data</code>' <br/> 
                            and or '<code>C:\Users\[YourUser]\OneDrive\Apps\GradeMaster\Data</code>'. <br/>
                            GradeMaster now features extensive database management tools for managing the data of the app.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Notes:</strong>
                        <p>Notes in GradeMaster are made for making notes about your education or stuff relevant to your education. The content of notes can and should be written in the Markdown format. <br/>
                            You can add Tags to your notes by using the following convention: "tag1, tag2, tag3". (separated by the comma) <br/>
                            You can also add links to different websites or pages of the app by using the Markdown link format: "[Link Text](https://example.com)". <br/>
                            For this functionality, the app offers the copy button on all entities, to copy the individual page URL to include as Link in the Note content. <br/>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer">
                        <strong>Search:</strong>
                        <p>When searching you can use following advanced patterns on following pages.</p>
                        <ul>
                            <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer-sm">
                                <strong>Educations:</strong> Patterns: "#1 some text | #2 some text" this will search for everything matching (#1) and institution matching (2#). Example: "Something specific | Institute1". <br/>
                                It is also possible to search for only "completed" or "in progress" entries. <br/>
                                In order to search for the completion state just add (complete) or (c) / (in progress) or (ip) at the end of your search. <br/>
                                You can also just search for completion state when you add an asterisk in front of the completion state you want to search for. Example: "*(complete)" or "*(c)" or "*(in progress)" or "*(ip)".
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer-sm">
                                <strong>Subjects:</strong> Patterns: Supports the pattern of Educations Page, but also allows you to search for subject with a combination of the subject name and subject semester. Example: "Some name 3" or "Some name - 3". <br/>
                                It is also possible to combine this with the search of institution. Example: "Some name 3 | Institute1". <br/>
                                It is also possible to search for only "completed" or "in progress" entries. <br/>
                                In order to search for the completion state just add (complete) or (c) / (in progress) or (ip) at the end of your search. <br/>
                                You can also just search for completion state when you add an asterisk in front of the completion state you want to search for. Example: "*(complete)" or "*(c)" or "*(in progress)" or "*(ip)".
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-item-bottom-spacer-sm">
                                <strong>Grades:</strong> Patterns: Supports the same patterns as the Subject page search. <br/> Search with completion state is not possible on this page.
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <strong>Notes:</strong> Patterns: "#1 some text | #2 some text" this will search for everything matching (#1) and color matching (#2). Example: "Something specific | red" or "Something specific | 🔴" or even "Something specific | red🔴". <br/>
                                It is also possible to search for only "archived" entries. <br/>
                                Similarly to searching for archived notes, you can also search for "pinned" notes. <br/>
                                In order to search for the archived notes just add (archived) or (a) at the end of your search. <br/>
                                In order to search for pinned notes just add (pinned) or (p) at the end of your search. <br/>
                                Here are some examples: "Some text (archived)", "Some text (a)", "Some text | red (a)", "Some text (pinned)", "Some text (p)", "Some text | red (p)". <br/>
                                You can also just search for archived or pinned notes when you add an asterisk in front of the archived or pinned state you want to search for. Example: "*(archived)" or "*(a)" or "*(pinned)" or "*(p)".
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
